VGUDIPOODI SRIHARIGUDIPOODI SRIHARIThough it was almost a last minute decision, the Department of Culture took a laudable step to celebrate the 89th jayanti of Bharat RatnaM. S. Subbulakshmi. South Indian Cultural Association and Raksha International put together  this commemoration programme, inviting a number of front rank musicians of the twin cities to render compositions of the many Vaggeyakaras.Most of them rightly chose to sing those songspopularised by Subbulakshmi. This proved once again that the late melody queen is the heartbeat of the many musicians here. The backstage was specially designed with an imposing picture of Subbulakshmi . The programme was titledBhaja Govindam, from the  cassette ofslokascomposed by Sri Jagadguru Adi Shankara in a song form inRagamalika, made famous of by the late M.S.Subbulakshmi and Raksha International Foundation.Sisters Lavanyalatha and Nityasanthoshini presented a mellifluous recital that includedGanesha Panchakam, Bhavayami Gopala Balam(of Annamacharya in Yamuna Kalyani) andMadhurashtakam Slokasof Adi Shankara. Sai Anil on the violin, P.V. Ramanamurthy ( mridangam), Ravi Kiran ( flute) and Sridharachari (tabla) accompanied the duo.Chitra Nagraj, a film playback singer too, rendered the famous morning songSrimannarayanaof Annamacharya inBowli, a Dikshitar composition,KanjadalayatakshiinKamalamanohariand TamilJawali. Seshulatha, Neetha and M.Padma, faculty of Music, Telugu University, next, were accompanied by Dinkar ( violin) and G. Ramachandran ( mridangam) accompanied.Ramanannu BrovarainHarikambhoji,Sada Saranga NayaneinRanjaniandAkhilandeswariinDwijavanthi, of Dikshitar and aDhanasri Tillanaof Swathi Tirunal constituted their melodious fare. An imposing recital by the popular Hyderabad Sisters, Lalitha and Haripriya, gave right finish to this occasion. Accompanied by Poosarla Manorama on violin, D.S.R. Murthy on mridangam and P V Ramanamurthy on ghatam, the duo presentedKamakoti Peetha SthitheinSaveriandBrochevarevaruinKhamas.Bottom Template Starts
